## ⚙️ Architectural Flow (How it works)

```mermaid
graph TD
    Client[React Frontend] -->|REST / JWT| API[API Service]
    API -->|Save Code| DB[(PostgreSQL)]
    API -->|Queue Analysis Task| MQ[RabbitMQ]
    
    MQ -->|Consume Task| Worker[Worker Service]
    Worker -->|Analyze Code| AI[AI Models / Heuristics]
    Worker -->|Update Status| Redis[(Redis Pub/Sub)]
    Worker -->|Save Results| DB
    
    Redis -->|SSE Updates| API
    API -->|Real-time Status| Client
    
    Prometheus -->|Scrape Metrics| API
    Prometheus -->|Scrape Metrics| Worker
    Grafana -->|Visualize| Prometheus
```

### 1. Authentication Handshake
- Users securely register and log in via the `api-service`.
- The system uses **Stateless Tokens** (RSA-signed JWTs) for all subsequent authenticated communication, ensuring secure access.

### 2. Project & File Flow
- Users create projects and upload source code snippets through the React frontend.
- The `api-service` securely stores the raw code in the PostgreSQL database and immediately returns an acknowledgment to the user.

### 3. Asynchronous AI Analysis Vector
- Once code is uploaded, an analysis request is pushed to RabbitMQ.
- The `worker-service` picks up the task, applies static heuristics, or queries AI providers (e.g., OpenAI, Groq) to evaluate the code for space/time complexity, bugs, security vulnerabilities, and optimal design patterns.
- Progress updates are sent through **Redis Pub/Sub**, which the `api-service` streams back to the frontend using Server-Sent Events (SSE) so the user sees real-time progress.

### 4. Observability
- All infrastructure components (DB, MQ, Cache) are isolated within a dedicated Docker network.
- Prometheus constantly scrapes health data, while Grafana gives administrators a real-time window into the system's operational stability.
